I never used java.util.logging, so I don't know whether my suggestion is useful, but netherless:
try to use different instance of java.util.logging.Logger, so not all 240 threads will be blocked on the same monitor
(it will help if different instances of Logger use different instances of java.util.logging.ConsoleHandler) .

node.contents: Flushing after each log record is going to expensive if you have very verbose logs.

astNode.text: Flushing after each log record is going to expensive if you have very verbose logs.

node.contents: A quality fix would be to clean up the logging, probably based around auditing.

astNode.text: A quality fix would be to clean up the logging, probably based around auditing.

node.contents: As a quick fix, override StreamHandler.flush or OutputStream.flush to not do so immediately. Only flush once every so often. Note, however that you could potentially lose logging data immediately before a crash if you do this.

astNode.text: As a quick fix, override StreamHandler.flush or OutputStream.flush to not do so immediately. Only flush once every so often. Note, however that you could potentially lose logging data immediately before a crash if you do this.

node.contents: According to your log, the issue concerns the use of java.util.logging.ConsoleHandler.

astNode.text: According to your log, the issue concerns the use of java.util.logging.ConsoleHandler.

node.contents: First try to disable the console handler by removing it from the 'handlers' and '.handlers' list in '${TOMCAT_HOME}/conf/logging.properties'. See whether the problem still occurs.

astNode.text: First try to disable the console handler by removing it from the 'handlers' and '.handlers' list in '${TOMCAT_HOME}/conf/logging.properties'. See whether the problem still occurs.

node.contents: If that helps, than it is definitely an issue with the output of the ConsoleHandler. Try checking whether there is are issues concerning the 'catalina.out' file. This is the file to where tomcat redirects its console output.

node.contents: I don't think this is an issue with Thread safety. It would have broken much earlier. 240 Threads is not a problem for the JVM. 240 Threads editing a single file could be. An ugly fix would be to reduce the amount of logged messages. Try tweaking the thing using getLoggerNames(), getLogger() and setLevel() from http://download-llnw.oracle.com/javase/1.4.2/docs/api/java/util/logging/LogManager.html and http://download-llnw.oracle.com/javase/1.4.2/docs/api/java/util/logging/Logger.html

node.contents: I think this is the right track. I'd look at external factors. Also, if it's writing not to a traditional file but to a Unix named pipe, make sure that somebody is reading the other end of the pipe at a sufficient pace. If the buffer fills up you'll just block.

node.contents: All your Threads are logging things. They all need to write on the disk from time to time. Everytime one of your 240 threads hits a logging line there will be disk access issues.

node.contents: If you are running under Windows and the java application starts a console, be careful not to click in the DOS box. Window's crappy mark and copy "feature" blocks output to the ConsoleHandler. So any logger trying to write to the screen will block. Writing to the Console is done in a native call and so the java thread will appear to be in a RUNNING state when in fact it is blocked, it's just there's no way to feed that blocked status back to the application (because you are in native space).
